WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:02.670 --> 00:00:05.180
FEMALE SPEAKER: Chef
Hugh is a father.

00:00:05.180 --> 00:00:06.280
He's a chef.

00:00:06.280 --> 00:00:09.290
He's an educating advocate.

00:00:09.290 --> 00:00:13.140
He is the owner of two amazing
restaurants in the South,

00:00:13.140 --> 00:00:16.630
in Atlanta-- the 5 &amp;
10 and the National.

00:00:16.630 --> 00:00:19.650
What was most striking
about, chef, your bio,

00:00:19.650 --> 00:00:23.580
you're self-trained--
no culinary school.

00:00:23.580 --> 00:00:30.540
So you can be this, too,
and get on "Top Chef."

00:00:30.540 --> 00:00:33.980
What is so interesting and
wonderful about Chef Hugh

00:00:33.980 --> 00:00:37.350
and why we wanted to work
with him is just this passion

00:00:37.350 --> 00:00:39.060
you have about
teaching life skills

00:00:39.060 --> 00:00:41.230
to all people and communities.

00:00:41.230 --> 00:00:45.170
So without more, I just
want to introduce Chef Hugh.

00:00:45.170 --> 00:00:45.730
Welcome.

00:00:45.730 --> 00:00:46.350
HUGH ACHESON: Well, thank you.

00:00:46.350 --> 00:00:48.266
FEMALE SPEAKER: And we're
excited to have you.

00:00:48.266 --> 00:00:49.700
And welcome to all the Googlers.

00:00:49.700 --> 00:00:54.250
[APPLAUSE]

00:00:54.250 --> 00:00:55.970
HUGH ACHESON: So
I'm Hugh Acheson.

00:00:55.970 --> 00:00:59.334
I'm 522 months old.

00:00:59.334 --> 00:01:03.160
And I have two kids.

00:01:03.160 --> 00:01:05.830
And a lot of what we're
going to talk about

00:01:05.830 --> 00:01:11.100
is a direct reaction to what
I see my kids going through

00:01:11.100 --> 00:01:14.650
and what I want them
to attain in the world.

00:01:14.650 --> 00:01:18.040
So, yeah, the story with
Beatrice is Beatrice was 11

00:01:18.040 --> 00:01:19.780
and came home from school.

00:01:19.780 --> 00:01:21.020
And let me first say this.

00:01:21.020 --> 00:01:22.710
Our school district is great.

00:01:22.710 --> 00:01:24.210
A lot of school
districts are great.

00:01:24.210 --> 00:01:26.110
They're trying really hard.

00:01:26.110 --> 00:01:29.510
But sometimes we need to
inject newness into curriculums

00:01:29.510 --> 00:01:31.070
to make them that much better.

00:01:31.070 --> 00:01:34.080
So she came home from her first
day of family and consumer

00:01:34.080 --> 00:01:36.455
sciences, which is the
gender nonspecific term

00:01:36.455 --> 00:01:39.080
for home economics because home
economics became something that

00:01:39.080 --> 00:01:43.330
was teaching very much like
"how to raise your baby" type

00:01:43.330 --> 00:01:47.616
of skills, which we'll all learn
on our own someday in life.

00:01:47.616 --> 00:01:49.240
And maybe we need a
little bit of that,

00:01:49.240 --> 00:01:52.780
but what I wanted it to
teach was life skills.

00:01:52.780 --> 00:01:55.890
Yet it taught Beatrice how
to make red velvet cupcakes

00:01:55.890 --> 00:01:59.060
from a box and how to pull
croissants out of a Pillsbury

00:01:59.060 --> 00:02:01.090
tube and wrap them
in cheap bacon

00:02:01.090 --> 00:02:03.990
and bake them in the oven--
and to take prenatal vitamins

00:02:03.990 --> 00:02:06.640
at 11, which I don't really
ethically-- ethically I

00:02:06.640 --> 00:02:07.625
don't care about.

00:02:07.625 --> 00:02:09.500
Usually the vitamins
are like named something

00:02:09.500 --> 00:02:14.100
like One-A-Day, which implies
the direction in the title.

00:02:14.100 --> 00:02:16.440
So I didn't think that
was really necessary.

00:02:16.440 --> 00:02:18.630
And I started to think
about life skills.

00:02:18.630 --> 00:02:21.900
So I went to the school
superintendent for our region

00:02:21.900 --> 00:02:23.160
and started talking to him.

00:02:23.160 --> 00:02:25.710
And he said, yeah, I was about
to cancel that whole class

00:02:25.710 --> 00:02:27.460
because it sucks.

00:02:27.460 --> 00:02:29.640
And it got me thinking,
well, if it sucks

00:02:29.640 --> 00:02:31.710
and we yank it
out of the system,

00:02:31.710 --> 00:02:35.440
then we're still raising the
status quo, which is kids

00:02:35.440 --> 00:02:38.080
who have no idea how to cook.

00:02:38.080 --> 00:02:40.070
So I developed a curriculum.

00:02:40.070 --> 00:02:42.440
And I went to him and said,
I think we can do this.

00:02:42.440 --> 00:02:44.110
And he said, well,
why don't you do it?

00:02:44.110 --> 00:02:46.890
And I said because
I have five jobs.

00:02:46.890 --> 00:02:48.880
And I work 90 hours
a week already,

00:02:48.880 --> 00:02:50.990
and I try and raise my family.

00:02:50.990 --> 00:02:54.320
And so then I said,
OK, I'll do it.

00:02:54.320 --> 00:02:58.480
So we're going live in four
middle schools in grade six

00:02:58.480 --> 00:02:59.210
next year.

00:02:59.210 --> 00:03:00.834
Following year, we'll
have grade seven.

00:03:00.834 --> 00:03:02.620
Following year, we'll
have grade eight.

00:03:02.620 --> 00:03:05.420
The core curriculum
is nine things.

00:03:05.420 --> 00:03:09.510
It is a look at cooking overall,
which is really about five

00:03:09.510 --> 00:03:10.620
or six of the things.

00:03:10.620 --> 00:03:12.120
But it's life skills.

00:03:12.120 --> 00:03:13.947
It's retainable things.

00:03:13.947 --> 00:03:16.030
It's how to poach an egg,
which we're about to do.

00:03:16.030 --> 00:03:18.363
It's how to make a vinaigrette,
which we're about to do.

00:03:18.363 --> 00:03:20.170
It's how to build a
dinner effectively

00:03:20.170 --> 00:03:23.090
for like $8 for four people.

00:03:23.090 --> 00:03:26.240
It's things that hopefully
stick with people by the time

00:03:26.240 --> 00:03:28.496
they get to 18, 19, 20-- the
hardest time in your life

00:03:28.496 --> 00:03:30.870
when you have no money and
you're trying to figure things

00:03:30.870 --> 00:03:35.420
out and it's just
hard to figure out

00:03:35.420 --> 00:03:36.836
how to put dinner on the table.

00:03:36.836 --> 00:03:39.210
This is things you can hearken
back to and say at least I

00:03:39.210 --> 00:03:40.394
know how to poach an egg.

00:03:40.394 --> 00:03:41.810
Well, right now
we just don't have

00:03:41.810 --> 00:03:45.290
that sort of life skills
being obtained by children.

00:03:45.290 --> 00:03:46.804
So this is that
way of doing that.

00:03:46.804 --> 00:03:48.470
But it's also got a
lot of home finance.

00:03:48.470 --> 00:03:49.770
It's got a lot of life hacks.

00:03:49.770 --> 00:03:51.160
It's got a lot of DIY.

00:03:51.160 --> 00:03:54.660
It's got a lot of basic
sewing because I was cool when

00:03:54.660 --> 00:03:56.550
I was 12 because I could sew.

00:03:56.550 --> 00:03:58.380
And I was a dude.

00:03:58.380 --> 00:04:00.510
It was weird, but it
was really helpful.

00:04:00.510 --> 00:04:03.750
And I still hem my own
pants-- not this pair.

00:04:03.750 --> 00:04:06.140
So these are all life skills.

00:04:06.140 --> 00:04:09.490
And I'll go over them
specifically in a little bit.

00:04:09.490 --> 00:04:12.720
But what I think the most
telling thing about when

00:04:12.720 --> 00:04:15.600
I explain this to people--
to doctors and lawyers

00:04:15.600 --> 00:04:20.040
and hedge fund managers in New
York and coders and people who

00:04:20.040 --> 00:04:25.240
work at big companies like you
all do-- is that they all say,

00:04:25.240 --> 00:04:27.500
do you have a program
that I could take?

00:04:27.500 --> 00:04:29.390
Because I'm not in
grade 6, because I need

00:04:29.390 --> 00:04:31.220
to learn all that stuff, too.

00:04:31.220 --> 00:04:35.290
Because you guys are super
smart, amazing, amazingly

00:04:35.290 --> 00:04:37.340
productive people,
but a lot of you

00:04:37.340 --> 00:04:39.270
have no idea how
to effectively put

00:04:39.270 --> 00:04:42.640
dinner on the table that's
from scratch for your kids

00:04:42.640 --> 00:04:44.930
or even just for yourself.

00:04:44.930 --> 00:04:46.410
So these are life skills.

00:04:46.410 --> 00:04:48.880
And I think that we
raise a better tomorrow

00:04:48.880 --> 00:04:51.930
when we get all kids
knowing these basic things.

00:04:51.930 --> 00:04:54.890
So if we have every kid knowing
how to poach an egg in America,

00:04:54.890 --> 00:04:55.790
this is great.

00:04:55.790 --> 00:04:57.960
So that's the end
result of this,

00:04:57.960 --> 00:04:59.640
is hopefully that type of thing.

00:04:59.640 --> 00:05:02.350
What we're trying to do in
building the curriculum is

00:05:02.350 --> 00:05:04.510
we're having a big
charrette next month

00:05:04.510 --> 00:05:07.300
with a lot of food policy people
and lawyers and architects

00:05:07.300 --> 00:05:10.840
and designers and painters
and artists and coders

00:05:10.840 --> 00:05:13.090
and all these different
people coming together saying,

00:05:13.090 --> 00:05:15.110
what do we all need to learn?

00:05:15.110 --> 00:05:17.170
What, as citizens,
do we all need

00:05:17.170 --> 00:05:20.400
to know universally
when it applies to food,

00:05:20.400 --> 00:05:23.370
and reading a lease, and
opening up your first bank

00:05:23.370 --> 00:05:25.900
account, and all these
things that would contribute

00:05:25.900 --> 00:05:27.620
to our wherewithal as humans.

00:05:27.620 --> 00:05:28.746
What are those things?

00:05:28.746 --> 00:05:30.370
So that's what we're
whittling down to.

00:05:30.370 --> 00:05:31.500
And that comes in a month.

00:05:31.500 --> 00:05:34.050
But we've already
got the basic idea.

00:05:34.050 --> 00:05:36.930
So what I want to
do here is really

00:05:36.930 --> 00:05:39.610
to hearken back to
this idea of food.

00:05:39.610 --> 00:05:42.070
Now what happened with
food in the last 50 years

00:05:42.070 --> 00:05:45.310
is that we all fell hook,
line, and sinker for fast food,

00:05:45.310 --> 00:05:47.180
frozen food, prepackaged food.

00:05:47.180 --> 00:05:48.890
Everything became so easy.

00:05:48.890 --> 00:05:52.020
But as we stripped
away our skill sets,

00:05:52.020 --> 00:05:54.490
and as we forgot how to
cook, and we say things like,

00:05:54.490 --> 00:05:57.170
I used to make jam
with my grandmother,

00:05:57.170 --> 00:06:00.420
we don't say things like I
used to make jam with my mother

00:06:00.420 --> 00:06:04.080
because mom fed us Smucker's.

00:06:04.080 --> 00:06:06.550
And we lost a skill
set when she did that.

00:06:06.550 --> 00:06:10.280
And we didn't pass along from
generation to generation core

00:06:10.280 --> 00:06:13.380
ideas of what we value
and what we believe in.

00:06:13.380 --> 00:06:15.440
So this is trying
to get back to that

00:06:15.440 --> 00:06:17.240
and trying to get to
that basic necessity.

00:06:17.240 --> 00:06:20.320
It's kind of homesteading skills
for the urban environment.

00:06:20.320 --> 00:06:21.870
So let's go over
what we're going

00:06:21.870 --> 00:06:26.780
to cook today because it's
very, very beautifully basic.

00:06:26.780 --> 00:06:30.510
When we talk about whole food
and the ease of whole food

00:06:30.510 --> 00:06:33.090
and defeating this
era of convenience,

00:06:33.090 --> 00:06:35.780
if this is inconvenient,
I don't know what's

00:06:35.780 --> 00:06:37.470
really inconvenient about it.

00:06:37.470 --> 00:06:39.250
Because this, we're
going to make a salad.

00:06:39.250 --> 00:06:41.230
So first we're going
to cook some farro.

00:06:41.230 --> 00:06:42.750
Cooked farro looks like this.

00:06:42.750 --> 00:06:44.110
Farro's a whole grain.

00:06:44.110 --> 00:06:45.760
It's an emmer wheat.

00:06:45.760 --> 00:06:47.160
And it is an integral grain.

00:06:47.160 --> 00:06:49.920
Sometimes it's washed and
stripped of the outer coating.

00:06:49.920 --> 00:06:53.640
You want to find stuff that's
complete and still whole.

00:06:53.640 --> 00:06:56.710
So that's going to go
into this pot over here.

00:06:56.710 --> 00:06:58.150
And again, we're
going to show you

00:06:58.150 --> 00:07:01.220
how to cook grains, which is not
rocket science because that's

00:07:01.220 --> 00:07:02.880
two cups of water.

00:07:02.880 --> 00:07:03.970
And that's a cup of farro.

00:07:03.970 --> 00:07:05.470
And we're going to
put that in there

00:07:05.470 --> 00:07:06.830
and season with a little salt.

00:07:06.830 --> 00:07:07.415
What's salt?

00:07:10.240 --> 00:07:11.564
Salt is a seasoning.

00:07:11.564 --> 00:07:12.980
It brings out
flavor in our palate

00:07:12.980 --> 00:07:14.332
and brings out flavor in food.

00:07:14.332 --> 00:07:15.790
So we're going to
add that to that.

00:07:15.790 --> 00:07:17.210
And we're going to
bring it to a boil.

00:07:17.210 --> 00:07:18.250
And then we're
going to simmer it.

00:07:18.250 --> 00:07:19.310
And it's going to be done.

00:07:19.310 --> 00:07:20.893
So you can just look
away from things.

00:07:20.893 --> 00:07:22.440
That's really easy.

00:07:22.440 --> 00:07:24.180
Believe in leftovers.

00:07:24.180 --> 00:07:26.910
If you're cooking for a family,
and you make roasted chicken

00:07:26.910 --> 00:07:29.450
the night before with
farro, make extra farro

00:07:29.450 --> 00:07:31.200
because the next day
you can take a salad,

00:07:31.200 --> 00:07:32.720
and pack a salad
for the kids that's

00:07:32.720 --> 00:07:35.010
pretty much this with
salad dressing on the side.

00:07:35.010 --> 00:07:37.050
It makes things easier.

00:07:37.050 --> 00:07:40.330
So if you work 13 hours
a day, which you all do,

00:07:40.330 --> 00:07:42.970
I want to make sure that you
understand that the time it

00:07:42.970 --> 00:07:45.660
takes to make a meal like
this is equivalent to going

00:07:45.660 --> 00:07:48.000
to a Chick-fil-A drive-through.

00:07:48.000 --> 00:07:49.430
It's a confused
chicken sandwich.

00:07:49.430 --> 00:07:50.610
I admit it's good.

00:07:50.610 --> 00:07:54.010
But it's politically--
it's a little shaky.

00:07:54.010 --> 00:07:56.730
But what I want to do is
that 15 minutes that you

00:07:56.730 --> 00:07:59.670
spend in line waiting
there, you can cook dinner

00:07:59.670 --> 00:08:01.650
around your family
as they do homework

00:08:01.650 --> 00:08:03.090
or as they sit and play.

00:08:03.090 --> 00:08:06.010
And you would be amazed
at how kids learn.

00:08:06.010 --> 00:08:08.480
I think we all have this
idea and inclination

00:08:08.480 --> 00:08:09.700
that we know how kids learn.

00:08:09.700 --> 00:08:12.030
Kids learn by experience,
by watching you,

00:08:12.030 --> 00:08:14.990
by watching you be comfortable
in your environment

00:08:14.990 --> 00:08:15.680
of a kitchen.

00:08:15.680 --> 00:08:17.930
Your kitchen is the most
important room in your house.

00:08:17.930 --> 00:08:19.810
Use it.

00:08:19.810 --> 00:08:22.330
Don't be like a New Yorker and
store clothes in your oven.

00:08:22.330 --> 00:08:23.950
That's weird.

00:08:23.950 --> 00:08:25.240
So we're going to do that.

00:08:25.240 --> 00:08:28.740
As the farro is cooking--
it's come to a boil.

00:08:28.740 --> 00:08:30.950
I'm going to reduce
that down to a simmer.

00:08:30.950 --> 00:08:33.400
So that's going to
be at around three.

00:08:33.400 --> 00:08:34.850
This thing goes to 10.

00:08:34.850 --> 00:08:37.580
It may be the spinal tap
version that goes to 11,

00:08:37.580 --> 00:08:39.768
but I don't think so.

00:08:39.768 --> 00:08:41.059
So I'm just going to stir that.

00:08:41.059 --> 00:08:43.159
And we're going to
cap it and let it sit.

00:08:43.159 --> 00:08:45.270
And that's going to take
about 20 minutes to cook.

00:08:45.270 --> 00:08:47.070
So we're going to
make a vinaigrette.

00:08:47.070 --> 00:08:49.920
It's funny the whole
aisle in the supermarket

00:08:49.920 --> 00:08:53.920
is devoted to dressings
and salad dressings

00:08:53.920 --> 00:08:56.660
when things like mayonnaise
and salad dressings

00:08:56.660 --> 00:08:59.960
are really easy to effectively
make at home from scratch.

00:08:59.960 --> 00:09:03.010
They're oftentimes totally
preservative-free when

00:09:03.010 --> 00:09:06.230
we make them that way, too,
and much healthier for you.

00:09:06.230 --> 00:09:08.380
The way I think I want
to eat in this world

00:09:08.380 --> 00:09:10.840
is knowing what I'm
putting into my body

00:09:10.840 --> 00:09:12.950
and training myself
to understand

00:09:12.950 --> 00:09:14.540
that if something's
pre-prepared,

00:09:14.540 --> 00:09:16.390
I don't know exactly
what's going into it.

00:09:16.390 --> 00:09:18.900
And a lot of times, it's
packed with sugars and things

00:09:18.900 --> 00:09:22.430
like that that we
don't necessarily need.

00:09:22.430 --> 00:09:25.770
There's a lot of food out
there that we are really

00:09:25.770 --> 00:09:29.590
led to believe is good
for us, and it's not.

00:09:29.590 --> 00:09:31.390
This is one fascinating thing.

00:09:31.390 --> 00:09:35.780
Frosted Flakes and Raisin
Bran, which has more sugar?

00:09:35.780 --> 00:09:37.070
Raisin Bran.

00:09:37.070 --> 00:09:38.780
Isn't that insane?

00:09:38.780 --> 00:09:40.540
I feel like we've been lied to.

00:09:40.540 --> 00:09:42.010
But OK, that's fine.

00:09:42.010 --> 00:09:43.070
We're moving on.

00:09:43.070 --> 00:09:45.090
So what's a vinaigrette?

00:09:45.090 --> 00:09:46.860
Vinaigrette's a ratio.

00:09:46.860 --> 00:09:51.990
A lot of you do crazy math
or accounting or coding.

00:09:51.990 --> 00:09:54.009
You want to attribute
things to numbers.

00:09:54.009 --> 00:09:54.800
Well, it's a ratio.

00:09:54.800 --> 00:10:00.350
It's three to one richness
in oil and one as in acids.

00:10:00.350 --> 00:10:03.280
I want to make this a
little more bracingly acidic

00:10:03.280 --> 00:10:06.310
because in the end, it's going
to be a salad with vegetables

00:10:06.310 --> 00:10:11.800
and lettuce and farro, but also
this puppy, which is an egg.

00:10:11.800 --> 00:10:16.340
And an egg on your palate
is much like eating fat.

00:10:16.340 --> 00:10:19.480
So I want to balance with
hyper-acidic vinaigrette

00:10:19.480 --> 00:10:22.460
to balance the fact that this
is more oil essentially going

00:10:22.460 --> 00:10:24.430
into my ratio of a vinaigrette.

00:10:24.430 --> 00:10:25.317
Makes sense?

00:10:25.317 --> 00:10:27.150
So I'm going to amp it
up just a little bit.

00:10:27.150 --> 00:10:29.330
So this is extra
virgin olive oil.

00:10:29.330 --> 00:10:31.940
You don't have to buy the
most expensive olive oil,

00:10:31.940 --> 00:10:33.681
but I don't think
at the pearly gates

00:10:33.681 --> 00:10:35.180
or wherever you're
going after this,

00:10:35.180 --> 00:10:37.471
you're going to feel that
bad about buying better olive

00:10:37.471 --> 00:10:38.660
oil in this world.

00:10:38.660 --> 00:10:40.230
So treat yourself.

00:10:40.230 --> 00:10:44.050
So this is going to be
about three tablespoons.

00:10:44.050 --> 00:10:46.509
And then we're going to put
a whole clove of garlic in.

00:10:46.509 --> 00:10:48.300
And that's just going
to flavor it through.

00:10:48.300 --> 00:10:51.610
But I'm going to cut in half
just to expose the flavor.

00:10:51.610 --> 00:10:56.600
If you buy pre-minced
garlic, you've lost in life.

00:10:56.600 --> 00:11:00.200
So you just need to learn
how to mince garlic.

00:11:00.200 --> 00:11:01.500
It's not a big deal.

00:11:01.500 --> 00:11:03.230
Do you know how
to juice a lemon?

00:11:03.230 --> 00:11:04.752
Don't buy the plastic one.

00:11:04.752 --> 00:11:05.960
I don't know what's in there.

00:11:05.960 --> 00:11:07.790
But it's not cool.

00:11:07.790 --> 00:11:11.050
Then we're going to put a
little bit of mustard in here.

00:11:11.050 --> 00:11:13.430
Now these are all-- I'm
a big believer in food

00:11:13.430 --> 00:11:15.110
should not be precious.

00:11:15.110 --> 00:11:16.640
These are all
things you probably

00:11:16.640 --> 00:11:18.090
have around the house anyhow.

00:11:18.090 --> 00:11:19.910
So this is not confusing.

00:11:19.910 --> 00:11:23.390
A little bit of salt.
A little bit of pepper.

00:11:23.390 --> 00:11:26.260
And then some vinegar.

00:11:26.260 --> 00:11:30.480
Now you could use any type
of vinegar that you want.

00:11:30.480 --> 00:11:32.719
I'm using a cider
vinegar in this case.

00:11:32.719 --> 00:11:34.260
But you could use
a red wine vinegar.

00:11:34.260 --> 00:11:37.370
You can make your own vinegar
really easily as well.

00:11:37.370 --> 00:11:39.250
And then this goes in.

00:11:39.250 --> 00:11:41.550
And I'll tell you a little
Beatrice story in a second

00:11:41.550 --> 00:11:42.530
as I do this.

00:11:42.530 --> 00:11:43.450
Now this is that.

00:11:43.450 --> 00:11:45.650
We're going to make an
emulsification by this.

00:11:45.650 --> 00:11:46.950
So it's a workout as well.

00:11:46.950 --> 00:11:48.300
This is not confusing.

00:11:48.300 --> 00:11:48.869
This is food.

00:11:48.869 --> 00:11:51.160
I'm trying to make sure you're
stripping away this idea

00:11:51.160 --> 00:11:54.130
that food needs to be made
by somebody in a chef coat

00:11:54.130 --> 00:11:55.530
with a fancy apron on.

00:11:55.530 --> 00:11:58.410
I'm wearing a bespoke
apron right now.

00:11:58.410 --> 00:12:01.810
But it's not a fancy apron.

00:12:01.810 --> 00:12:03.274
So the vinaigrette's done.

00:12:03.274 --> 00:12:04.940
If you wanted to make
extra vinaigrette,

00:12:04.940 --> 00:12:06.610
you can make a ton of it
and store it in your fridge.

00:12:06.610 --> 00:12:09.220
It's going to stay good in the
fridge for three to four weeks

00:12:09.220 --> 00:12:09.880
easily.

00:12:09.880 --> 00:12:12.296
The only thing that's going
to go bad in this vinaigrette,

00:12:12.296 --> 00:12:14.580
really, is oil tends to
go rancid after a while.

00:12:14.580 --> 00:12:16.163
But it was probably
rancid because you

00:12:16.163 --> 00:12:19.250
bought it a year ago
anyhow in your cupboard.

00:12:19.250 --> 00:12:21.442
But the garlic in
there will go off, too.

00:12:21.442 --> 00:12:23.650
But that, really, is going
to take two to three weeks

00:12:23.650 --> 00:12:24.304
to happen.

00:12:24.304 --> 00:12:25.970
So you can make this
with fresh shallot.

00:12:25.970 --> 00:12:27.760
You can finally dice onion.

00:12:27.760 --> 00:12:30.340
Basically, the
ratio is the ratio.

00:12:30.340 --> 00:12:32.570
And if you want to flavor
it with chopped-up kimchi,

00:12:32.570 --> 00:12:33.359
that's great.

00:12:33.359 --> 00:12:34.900
You want to flavor
it with hot sauce,

00:12:34.900 --> 00:12:37.960
you want to use the lime
instead of some of the vinegar,

00:12:37.960 --> 00:12:40.939
you just need to understand that
it's all based on that ratio.

00:12:40.939 --> 00:12:42.980
And the flavor profile of
what you're looking for

00:12:42.980 --> 00:12:45.410
is anything you want to make it.

00:12:45.410 --> 00:12:47.540
On top of the ratio, you
can add different flavors.

00:12:47.540 --> 00:12:48.600
So it could be soy.

00:12:48.600 --> 00:12:50.140
And it could be ground sesame.

00:12:50.140 --> 00:12:53.120
It could be whatever it is--
tahini or whatever it is.

00:12:53.120 --> 00:12:54.770
So that's there.

00:12:54.770 --> 00:12:57.420
We're going to begin to process
through some vegetables.

00:12:57.420 --> 00:12:59.771
And then we're going
to look at our farro.

00:12:59.771 --> 00:13:01.020
I've already got cooked farro.

00:13:01.020 --> 00:13:02.670
So this is not really important.

00:13:02.670 --> 00:13:06.650
It's kind of the TV switcheroo.

00:13:06.650 --> 00:13:09.970
So in the recipes,
I broke them down.

00:13:09.970 --> 00:13:13.540
And literally, they are the
simplest vegetables and things

00:13:13.540 --> 00:13:15.500
to-- and simplest
recipes to make.

00:13:15.500 --> 00:13:17.820
So if I go home
and I'm starving,

00:13:17.820 --> 00:13:22.247
and my kids are by my side, I
would make Beatrice make this.

00:13:22.247 --> 00:13:23.830
Because let's go
back to when Beatrice

00:13:23.830 --> 00:13:25.913
was five years old and
going off to kindergarten--

00:13:25.913 --> 00:13:28.200
and this pulls at my
heartstrings as a dad,

00:13:28.200 --> 00:13:31.480
but also as a cook and
a chef and a proponent

00:13:31.480 --> 00:13:32.494
of homemade food.

00:13:32.494 --> 00:13:34.160
So I could hear this
clamoring first day

00:13:34.160 --> 00:13:35.451
of kindergarten in the kitchen.

00:13:35.451 --> 00:13:37.530
And Beatrice, I
can see looking out

00:13:37.530 --> 00:13:38.980
my bedroom into the kitchen.

00:13:38.980 --> 00:13:41.250
And Beatrice is there
standing on a stool

00:13:41.250 --> 00:13:45.004
with a knife in her hand cutting
vegetables to make a salad.

00:13:45.004 --> 00:13:47.170
And she was doing pretty
much what we're doing here.

00:13:47.170 --> 00:13:49.840
And she was putting it into a
bowl that's got a sealable lid.

00:13:49.840 --> 00:13:52.300
And she was shaking then a
vinaigrette off to the side

00:13:52.300 --> 00:13:54.090
and pouring a little bit
of that and sealing it.

00:13:54.090 --> 00:13:56.090
And that was her lunch
she was taking to school.

00:13:56.090 --> 00:13:57.700
Nobody instructed
her to do that.

00:13:57.700 --> 00:13:59.290
Nobody had taught
her to do that.

00:13:59.290 --> 00:14:01.540
She had learned that
by watching me work

00:14:01.540 --> 00:14:03.000
in the kitchen over the years.

00:14:03.000 --> 00:14:05.840
Really perceptive kid,
and she's a sponge.

00:14:05.840 --> 00:14:07.060
But that's what kids are.

00:14:07.060 --> 00:14:08.150
They're sponges.

00:14:08.150 --> 00:14:11.350
But Beatrice, just
as an example,

00:14:11.350 --> 00:14:14.800
will have a much better life
because of the skill sets,

00:14:14.800 --> 00:14:16.810
because of these
core ideas of food,

00:14:16.810 --> 00:14:20.400
that she understands that this
is not precious, this is easy.

00:14:20.400 --> 00:14:22.960
And that's what we need to get
across to this next generation

00:14:22.960 --> 00:14:25.810
because there are so
many temptations in how

00:14:25.810 --> 00:14:27.790
we feed ourselves every day.

00:14:27.790 --> 00:14:30.560
There's so much ease out
there and what we think

00:14:30.560 --> 00:14:31.370
is convenience.

00:14:31.370 --> 00:14:33.880
But that convenience
catches up to us.

00:14:33.880 --> 00:14:36.730
And that convenience has
caught up to our society

00:14:36.730 --> 00:14:39.540
in the form of type 2
diabetes and obesity

00:14:39.540 --> 00:14:41.320
and just loss of skill sets.

00:14:42.660 --> 00:14:43.640
So Beatrice did that.

00:14:43.640 --> 00:14:45.470
So I would go home now.

00:14:45.470 --> 00:14:47.110
And I'll get Bea to make that.

00:14:47.110 --> 00:14:49.360
I'll get Clem to make--
Clementine;s my other daughter

00:14:49.360 --> 00:14:50.830
who's 11-- to make farro.

00:14:50.830 --> 00:14:51.750
And she'll do it.

00:14:51.750 --> 00:14:55.660
And we'll talk about what
happened during the day.

00:14:55.660 --> 00:14:58.980
So cooking from scratch
is all about that.

00:14:58.980 --> 00:15:00.550
But it's also what I just said.

00:15:00.550 --> 00:15:05.160
We will talk about what
went on during the day.

00:15:05.160 --> 00:15:08.640
I mentioned this earlier
because it's really important.

00:15:08.640 --> 00:15:11.250
We do not have family
moments that we

00:15:11.250 --> 00:15:13.800
remember over Pizza Pockets.

00:15:13.800 --> 00:15:16.130
We have family moments
that we remember

00:15:16.130 --> 00:15:18.910
that mean a lot to
us in our community

00:15:18.910 --> 00:15:22.490
and in our household over
food we make from scratch.

00:15:22.490 --> 00:15:25.330
Nobody wants to remember
a meal of a Pizza Pocket

00:15:25.330 --> 00:15:26.640
because that's embarrassing.

00:15:26.640 --> 00:15:28.540
OK, carrying on.

00:15:28.540 --> 00:15:31.080
So I'm going to start
assembling my salad.

00:15:31.080 --> 00:15:34.080
So this is just a really
simple like Little Gem or Bibb

00:15:34.080 --> 00:15:35.930
lettuce.

00:15:35.930 --> 00:15:39.510
Let's be abundantly clear about
what I believe about in food.

00:15:39.510 --> 00:15:40.792
I am not a zealot.

00:15:40.792 --> 00:15:43.000
If you bought this at the
grocery store, that's fine.

00:15:43.000 --> 00:15:46.930
If you bought it on a
direct-to-your-door delivery

00:15:46.930 --> 00:15:48.375
site on the internet,
that's fine.

00:15:48.375 --> 00:15:50.250
If you stole it from
the cafeteria at Google,

00:15:50.250 --> 00:15:52.380
that's fine, too.

00:15:52.380 --> 00:15:56.720
What I want you to
do is just cook.

00:15:56.720 --> 00:15:59.850
The best possible scenario
is you go out and find

00:15:59.850 --> 00:16:01.300
the person who grew this stuff.

00:16:01.300 --> 00:16:04.770
And on a Saturday, you go to the
farmer's market with your kids.

00:16:04.770 --> 00:16:08.490
And your kids realize the
food doesn't just appear.

00:16:08.490 --> 00:16:13.680
The food is tended to
by somebody with hands

00:16:13.680 --> 00:16:18.590
and cultivates that out of love
and trials and tribulations

00:16:18.590 --> 00:16:22.130
and the difficulties of farming
in North America these days,

00:16:22.130 --> 00:16:23.520
and actually works at it.

00:16:23.520 --> 00:16:26.610
And that work ethic, if I can
get Beatrice and Clementine

00:16:26.610 --> 00:16:29.170
to understand that the
food does not just appear,

00:16:29.170 --> 00:16:32.380
it makes food more precious
and more appreciated.

00:16:32.380 --> 00:16:35.630
And I think that even kids have
a lot of empathy on situations

00:16:35.630 --> 00:16:40.100
and are more prone to eat a
carrot that they know the where

00:16:40.100 --> 00:16:42.810
it came from and
that somebody grew it

00:16:42.810 --> 00:16:44.620
and somebody took pride in it.

00:16:44.620 --> 00:16:47.370
Because we've lost pride
in food, and that's

00:16:47.370 --> 00:16:49.727
what we need to inject
back into the scenario.

00:16:49.727 --> 00:16:51.810
So I'm going to start
chopping up some vegetables.

00:16:51.810 --> 00:16:53.340
This could be any vegetable.

00:16:53.340 --> 00:16:56.950
If it was beautiful turnips,
Hakurei turnips and cucumber,

00:16:56.950 --> 00:16:59.190
or it could be the
radishes or carrots,

00:16:59.190 --> 00:17:01.490
but it could be
chopped up cabbage.

00:17:01.490 --> 00:17:03.340
Basically, I'm just
saying it's whatever

00:17:03.340 --> 00:17:04.560
you have in your fridge.

00:17:04.560 --> 00:17:05.440
It's all food.

00:17:05.440 --> 00:17:08.210
And I want you to use all
of it because the problem

00:17:08.210 --> 00:17:10.770
with modern America is
we basically buy twice

00:17:10.770 --> 00:17:12.119
as much food as we need.

00:17:12.119 --> 00:17:13.970
And we waste half of it.

00:17:13.970 --> 00:17:16.550
So that's up to
you to change that.

00:17:16.550 --> 00:17:19.800
But it's little steps to
a better, bigger step.

00:17:19.800 --> 00:17:23.319
So you have to start changing
the way we look at that.

00:17:23.319 --> 00:17:25.390
So a lot of people
say, well, I'm

00:17:25.390 --> 00:17:28.069
not going to get a
five-year-old a knife.

00:17:28.069 --> 00:17:29.940
I'd give a
five-year-old a knife.

00:17:29.940 --> 00:17:33.340
I'm actually more scared of
giving middle schoolers knives.

00:17:33.340 --> 00:17:35.360
And let's talk about
middle schoolers

00:17:35.360 --> 00:17:37.660
and how hard they
are to deal with.

00:17:37.660 --> 00:17:40.780
They are complete sponges and
want to learn life skills.

00:17:40.780 --> 00:17:42.910
They're also going
through a lot.

00:17:42.910 --> 00:17:45.440
And in the American
child these days,

00:17:45.440 --> 00:17:48.280
there's a lot of diversity in
what they're going through.

00:17:48.280 --> 00:17:50.260
We taught knife skills
to a group class.

00:17:50.260 --> 00:17:52.960
One kid cut
themselves on purpose,

00:17:52.960 --> 00:17:55.430
which is a difficult
reality to set into.

00:17:55.430 --> 00:17:58.790
So it's hard to justify giving
a bunch of knives to kids

00:17:58.790 --> 00:18:02.650
and telling them go at it.

00:18:02.650 --> 00:18:05.480
But most five-year-olds
actually probably cut better

00:18:05.480 --> 00:18:09.240
than you do because you need to
learn the basic skills of it.

00:18:09.240 --> 00:18:10.840
So when we talk
about knife skills,

00:18:10.840 --> 00:18:12.530
you want to find
something that's sharp.

00:18:12.530 --> 00:18:16.620
And that's good because
the wound's cleaner.

00:18:16.620 --> 00:18:21.490
But if you see how I'm cutting,
I'm processing through.

00:18:21.490 --> 00:18:24.470
And my actual--
this finger right

00:18:24.470 --> 00:18:27.100
here is actually
touching the blade.

00:18:27.100 --> 00:18:28.990
And my thumb is well behind.

00:18:28.990 --> 00:18:32.960
And I'm doing a
little claw thing.

00:18:32.960 --> 00:18:34.600
And slowly but
surely, I think what

00:18:34.600 --> 00:18:37.225
you want to do with kids is just
show them what to do, and then

00:18:37.225 --> 00:18:39.440
implore them to do
it better and safely,

00:18:39.440 --> 00:18:41.524
and realize what they're
working with with knives.

00:18:41.524 --> 00:18:43.564
But eventually they're
going to work with knives.

00:18:43.564 --> 00:18:45.280
And you shouldn't be
scared about that.

00:18:45.280 --> 00:18:47.510
So we're going to
do radishes as well.

00:18:47.510 --> 00:18:49.300
And I love radishes.

00:18:49.300 --> 00:18:51.810
And people are like, how do
I get kids to eat radishes?

00:18:51.810 --> 00:18:55.320
Well, you give them
radishes, for starters.

00:18:55.320 --> 00:18:57.340
A lot of people are like,
my kid won't eat that.

00:18:57.340 --> 00:18:59.055
It's like if you've
never tried--

00:18:59.055 --> 00:19:01.090
you know what we
don't do at my house?

00:19:01.090 --> 00:19:03.360
We don't talk about what's
on the plate that much.

00:19:03.360 --> 00:19:04.410
The plate is the plate.

00:19:04.410 --> 00:19:07.950
There's no demarcated point that
you have to eat the vegetables.

00:19:07.950 --> 00:19:09.090
It's just food.

00:19:09.090 --> 00:19:10.370
It's all food.

00:19:10.370 --> 00:19:11.790
It's a balanced food.

00:19:11.790 --> 00:19:14.500
If you want to get your kids
to try and try more things,

00:19:14.500 --> 00:19:15.850
eat family style.

00:19:15.850 --> 00:19:17.540
So the four of you,
or six of you--

00:19:17.540 --> 00:19:20.260
I don't know how big your
family is-- one of you, whatever

00:19:20.260 --> 00:19:22.260
it is, lay out the food.

00:19:22.260 --> 00:19:25.470
And if you've got a hungry
kid, they tend to go after it.

00:19:25.470 --> 00:19:30.250
If you've got a kid you fed a
saccharin sweet 5:30 snack to,

00:19:30.250 --> 00:19:32.980
your chances of success
at the 6:30 dinner

00:19:32.980 --> 00:19:35.200
are very, very diminished.

00:19:35.200 --> 00:19:36.510
Does that makes sense?

00:19:36.510 --> 00:19:37.910
Basically, they're not hungry.

00:19:37.910 --> 00:19:40.035
And basically, when they're
not really that hungry,

00:19:40.035 --> 00:19:42.285
they're going to become
pickier about the food they're

00:19:42.285 --> 00:19:42.890
going to eat.

00:19:42.890 --> 00:19:44.460
I'm not saying
starve your child.

00:19:44.460 --> 00:19:46.630
I'm saying you want to
push them to the fact

00:19:46.630 --> 00:19:49.250
that there is a dinnertime,
that we have demarcated meals

00:19:49.250 --> 00:19:50.920
throughout the day.

00:19:50.920 --> 00:19:52.950
I live my life
snacking in kitchens.

00:19:52.950 --> 00:19:55.030
It's not a great existence.

00:19:55.030 --> 00:19:59.230
It makes me slim, but I
never really eat full meals.

00:19:59.230 --> 00:20:00.140
It's a weird thing.

00:20:00.140 --> 00:20:01.150
But OK.

00:20:01.150 --> 00:20:05.560
So I think the 5:30
snack is not good.

00:20:05.560 --> 00:20:07.670
You also want to
pick snack foods.

00:20:07.670 --> 00:20:12.830
Snack time should be
like 3:30, not at 5:30.

00:20:12.830 --> 00:20:13.890
So this is easy.

00:20:13.890 --> 00:20:17.110
We've got our basic
salad made up.

00:20:17.110 --> 00:20:20.250
If you wanted to add something
and make this a full my plate

00:20:20.250 --> 00:20:22.590
experience of a
meal, what I would

00:20:22.590 --> 00:20:27.020
add would be feta cheese
or chopped-up chatter

00:20:27.020 --> 00:20:28.610
or whatever it is.

00:20:28.610 --> 00:20:31.160
And that's going to add
just a little more protein.

00:20:31.160 --> 00:20:33.500
If you want to add
tofu, you could.

00:20:33.500 --> 00:20:35.550
If you wanted to add
steak from last night,

00:20:35.550 --> 00:20:37.890
or that roasted chicken
pieces from last night,

00:20:37.890 --> 00:20:39.070
you can do that, too.

00:20:39.070 --> 00:20:40.450
It depends on what you want.

00:20:40.450 --> 00:20:43.600
To me, this is a great meal
for a lunch just as is.

00:20:43.600 --> 00:20:45.715
A dinner, I'd probably
add some protein.

00:20:48.310 --> 00:20:50.060
Really, we're looking
at three components.

00:20:50.060 --> 00:20:52.430
And they're all in the
recipes you've got.

00:20:52.430 --> 00:20:54.070
So we've got the farro on.

00:20:54.070 --> 00:20:55.970
We've got the vinaigrette done.

00:20:55.970 --> 00:20:59.090
And then we're going to
make the poached eggs.

00:20:59.090 --> 00:21:02.970
And then we're just going to
assemble everything and get it

00:21:02.970 --> 00:21:05.570
together.

00:21:05.570 --> 00:21:09.700
Let's go back to just
cost analysis just briefly

00:21:09.700 --> 00:21:13.610
because I think this pulls away
from the preciousness of food,

00:21:13.610 --> 00:21:14.350
too.

00:21:14.350 --> 00:21:17.760
Look, if you want to buy
$12 a dozen eggs that

00:21:17.760 --> 00:21:22.730
were from Martha, the egg-laying
chicken who is very pampered,

00:21:22.730 --> 00:21:23.310
that's great.

00:21:23.310 --> 00:21:24.610
You can buy those.

00:21:24.610 --> 00:21:30.260
America still is buying
$1.50 and $1.75 a dozen eggs.

00:21:30.260 --> 00:21:33.130
So if we equate price to
that, they're probably not

00:21:33.130 --> 00:21:34.330
the best eggs in the world.

00:21:34.330 --> 00:21:35.500
But there are eggs.

00:21:35.500 --> 00:21:38.120
And again, little
steps win this war.

00:21:38.120 --> 00:21:41.810
I'm not arguing about local and
sustainable organic right now.

00:21:41.810 --> 00:21:44.310
I'm arguing about
core cooking skills.

00:21:44.310 --> 00:21:45.817
I don't care where
people get it.

00:21:45.817 --> 00:21:47.400
I just want them to
cook from scratch.

00:21:47.400 --> 00:21:48.700
That's the first step.

00:21:48.700 --> 00:21:51.430
Better food sourcing,
that's the second step.

00:21:51.430 --> 00:21:54.220
Your ideal, which is buying
organically and locally

00:21:54.220 --> 00:21:56.940
and sustainably, that's
a distant third step.

00:21:56.940 --> 00:22:00.070
But we're way far away
from bridging that gap

00:22:00.070 --> 00:22:01.960
right now because
most of America

00:22:01.960 --> 00:22:03.150
has forgotten how to cook.

00:22:03.150 --> 00:22:05.050
So this is the first step.

00:22:05.050 --> 00:22:08.610
So in that argument
is to say this egg

00:22:08.610 --> 00:22:11.200
is worth about a quarter.

00:22:11.200 --> 00:22:14.090
The farro, a pound
of it's about $4

00:22:14.090 --> 00:22:15.860
and will feed about 16 people.

00:22:15.860 --> 00:22:19.460
So maybe this is $1, all of it.

00:22:19.460 --> 00:22:22.100
And then the vinaigrette,
you've got about probably $0.25

00:22:22.100 --> 00:22:23.210
a portion.

00:22:23.210 --> 00:22:25.280
Olive oil is more
expensive than you think.

00:22:25.280 --> 00:22:27.020
So that's maybe another $1.

00:22:27.020 --> 00:22:29.590
And your vegetables
are probably $3.

00:22:29.590 --> 00:22:33.340
So you're looking at kind of a
$6 meal for four people here.

00:22:33.340 --> 00:22:36.920
So this idea that the
automatic assumption in value

00:22:36.920 --> 00:22:38.530
is that we jump
to the Happy Meal

00:22:38.530 --> 00:22:40.250
as being the best
value available.

00:22:40.250 --> 00:22:43.050
Well, the Happy Meal is $4.50.

00:22:43.050 --> 00:22:45.560
So if you do that two times,
and the other value meal

00:22:45.560 --> 00:22:50.110
is at $6 each, you're suddenly
at around $20, $21, $22.

00:22:50.110 --> 00:22:51.180
It's not a value.

00:22:51.180 --> 00:22:52.369
We've been lied to.

00:22:52.369 --> 00:22:53.410
So we need to fight back.

00:22:53.410 --> 00:22:55.493
And the way we fight back
is we learn how to cook.

00:22:55.493 --> 00:22:58.560
We learn that this
is our modern value.

00:22:58.560 --> 00:23:00.530
So back to poaching eggs.

00:23:00.530 --> 00:23:01.670
What's poaching?

00:23:01.670 --> 00:23:03.970
It's not boiling.

00:23:03.970 --> 00:23:08.490
It's kind of the
Jacuzzi of cooking food.

00:23:08.490 --> 00:23:10.290
It's taking something
that wants to be

00:23:10.290 --> 00:23:13.010
in a nice warm
environment slowly,

00:23:13.010 --> 00:23:17.540
slowly cooking and sort of
nuancing it and coagulating

00:23:17.540 --> 00:23:20.690
protein to an end result
of a beautiful thing.

00:23:20.690 --> 00:23:23.950
I like my egg yolk to
be relatively soft,

00:23:23.950 --> 00:23:26.080
but just set up.

00:23:26.080 --> 00:23:28.824
It's sort of almost like
custardy in the center.

00:23:28.824 --> 00:23:30.740
So I break into it, and
there's a slight ooze.

00:23:30.740 --> 00:23:31.760
I don't want a liquid.

00:23:31.760 --> 00:23:33.700
So we're going to show
you how to do that.

00:23:33.700 --> 00:23:35.741
The first thing that's
going to go into the water

00:23:35.741 --> 00:23:40.350
is just a little bit of salt.
This water is at around 160,

00:23:40.350 --> 00:23:42.650
165.

00:23:42.650 --> 00:23:45.384
And so boiling is 212.

00:23:45.384 --> 00:23:47.050
So it's nowhere near
boiling, but you'll

00:23:47.050 --> 00:23:48.930
see just little
traces of bubbles

00:23:48.930 --> 00:23:50.642
on the bottom beginning to form.

00:23:50.642 --> 00:23:52.100
The other thing
I'm putting in here

00:23:52.100 --> 00:23:54.740
is just a little bit of vinegar.

00:23:54.740 --> 00:23:56.520
And this is just a
still white vinegar

00:23:56.520 --> 00:23:59.600
and that's just going to
help the egg whites coagulate

00:23:59.600 --> 00:24:02.340
just a little more
closely towards the yolk

00:24:02.340 --> 00:24:03.900
and not flutter around.

00:24:03.900 --> 00:24:06.300
So the first step is you've
got your water going.

00:24:06.300 --> 00:24:11.890
Realize you're putting four--
who universally travels here?

00:24:11.890 --> 00:24:13.060
Or internationally travels?

00:24:13.060 --> 00:24:15.434
If you travel in the universe,
you can tell me that, too,

00:24:15.434 --> 00:24:16.390
because that's cool.

00:24:16.390 --> 00:24:18.410
And that, we should
probably keep that hush-hush

00:24:18.410 --> 00:24:19.805
if you guys are
really doing that.

00:24:19.805 --> 00:24:20.470
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE].

00:24:20.470 --> 00:24:21.280
HUGH ACHESON: We understand.

00:24:21.280 --> 00:24:22.196
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE].

00:24:24.004 --> 00:24:26.420
HUGH ACHESON: I remember going
to Spain about 10 years ago

00:24:26.420 --> 00:24:28.170
and looking for eggs
at the grocery store.

00:24:28.170 --> 00:24:30.420
And it took me forever
because contrary

00:24:30.420 --> 00:24:34.950
to North American culture, they
don't refrigerate their eggs.

00:24:34.950 --> 00:24:36.320
I'm not a food safety expert.

00:24:36.320 --> 00:24:37.050
I'm a chef.

00:24:37.050 --> 00:24:39.540
You don't really need to
refrigerate your eggs, either.

00:24:39.540 --> 00:24:44.690
If you put this as straight
out of the fridge times four

00:24:44.690 --> 00:24:48.409
into 165-degree water, and
these are at 38 degrees,

00:24:48.409 --> 00:24:50.575
you're going to plunge the
temperature of that water

00:24:50.575 --> 00:24:52.770
to way below a
poaching temperature.

00:24:52.770 --> 00:24:55.130
It's kind of like putting
ice cubes in water.

00:24:55.130 --> 00:24:56.630
You're going to
chill it down a lot.

00:24:56.630 --> 00:24:59.780
Or frying chicken
and wondering why

00:24:59.780 --> 00:25:02.610
it's like poaching in oil after
you put it in there because it

00:25:02.610 --> 00:25:04.050
