00:25:04.050 --> 00:25:04.925
Does that make sense?

00:25:04.925 --> 00:25:06.966
So we want to bring these
up to room temperature.

00:25:06.966 --> 00:25:08.500
And then we're
going to add it in.

00:25:08.500 --> 00:25:12.130
So room temperature is
sort of 75, 70 to 75.

00:25:12.130 --> 00:25:15.930
That's not going to affect it
as much as them being 38 to 40.

00:25:15.930 --> 00:25:17.100
So those are that.

00:25:17.100 --> 00:25:20.930
We're going to create--
you can go-- you

00:25:20.930 --> 00:25:24.060
do this backwards in Australia.

00:25:24.060 --> 00:25:25.710
But we're going to go like that.

00:25:25.710 --> 00:25:28.930
And then that's just going to
help everything bind together.

00:25:28.930 --> 00:25:31.097
You see the white go around.

00:25:31.097 --> 00:25:32.680
And we're just going
to continue that.

00:25:32.680 --> 00:25:36.420
And that white's just going
to grab on to that as we go.

00:25:36.420 --> 00:25:37.980
And you see it
beginning to grab on.

00:25:37.980 --> 00:25:41.110
As it's swirling, it wants
to grab back on to that.

00:25:41.110 --> 00:25:43.370
And it's doing exactly
what it's supposed to do.

00:25:43.370 --> 00:25:47.380
Just want to make sure it's
not sticking, which it's not.

00:25:47.380 --> 00:25:52.080
Right now this is at six
out of 10, which is 60%.

00:25:52.080 --> 00:25:54.625
Math class was very good to me.

00:25:54.625 --> 00:25:56.250
So we're just going
to stir that again.

00:25:56.250 --> 00:25:57.947
And again, we're going
to drop those in.

00:25:57.947 --> 00:26:00.030
You can drop all four in,
which we're going to do.

00:26:00.030 --> 00:26:03.370
I do put them in these little
ramekins ahead of time.

00:26:03.370 --> 00:26:05.390
And that just-- ooh,
that's a big yolk.

00:26:05.390 --> 00:26:07.190
The other ones were little.

00:26:07.190 --> 00:26:07.690
Eggs.

00:26:11.240 --> 00:26:13.490
Food, the modern miracle.

00:26:13.490 --> 00:26:15.010
So we're stirring that around.

00:26:15.010 --> 00:26:17.062
And we're just going
to get that in there.

00:26:17.062 --> 00:26:20.420
And stirring it around
just a little bit.

00:26:20.420 --> 00:26:23.657
I don't want to break my yolks.

00:26:23.657 --> 00:26:24.990
Now we're going to let those go.

00:26:24.990 --> 00:26:26.948
It's going to take about
three to four minutes.

00:26:26.948 --> 00:26:30.829
But what I want you to do is
realize that you read a recipe,

00:26:30.829 --> 00:26:32.870
and you read through it
and you think you got it,

00:26:32.870 --> 00:26:34.120
and nothing really goes right.

00:26:34.120 --> 00:26:37.590
Well, food is a nuanced thing.

00:26:37.590 --> 00:26:38.680
We love restaurants.

00:26:38.680 --> 00:26:40.560
Sometimes they're
really consistent.

00:26:40.560 --> 00:26:42.487
But that's a really
difficult thing to do.

00:26:42.487 --> 00:26:44.070
It's doing something--
I mean, there's

00:26:44.070 --> 00:26:45.970
a lot of different
things going on

00:26:45.970 --> 00:26:48.250
and a lot of different
people's responsibilities

00:26:48.250 --> 00:26:49.170
in the kitchen.

00:26:49.170 --> 00:26:51.360
So you just want to
watch it and begin

00:26:51.360 --> 00:26:53.540
to understand the
nuance of food and when

00:26:53.540 --> 00:26:55.110
things are naturally done.

00:26:55.110 --> 00:26:58.320
So in getting this
together as a final,

00:26:58.320 --> 00:27:03.893
I want to give a little bit of
toothsomeness-- how are you;

00:27:03.893 --> 00:27:05.740
you're good-- to this pharaoh.

00:27:05.740 --> 00:27:07.710
So it's cooked already.

00:27:07.710 --> 00:27:08.650
It's plumped out.

00:27:08.650 --> 00:27:13.090
It's tender, but
not really soft.

00:27:13.090 --> 00:27:15.150
But I'm going to crisp
it up by just putting

00:27:15.150 --> 00:27:18.940
a little bit of oil in the
pan, getting this heat up

00:27:18.940 --> 00:27:21.970
to about seven, and
then we're going to just

00:27:21.970 --> 00:27:23.055
put a little bit of it in.

00:27:23.055 --> 00:27:26.370
And I just want to give it
a little different crunch

00:27:26.370 --> 00:27:27.810
on the palate.

00:27:27.810 --> 00:27:31.070
And this is, again,
kids like texture.

00:27:31.070 --> 00:27:32.850
We like texture in food.

00:27:32.850 --> 00:27:36.390
I think we like big
flavors more than ever.

00:27:36.390 --> 00:27:38.690
We've internationalized
our food in North

00:27:38.690 --> 00:27:40.300
America in the last
five years more

00:27:40.300 --> 00:27:42.350
than it ever has in like 100.

00:27:42.350 --> 00:27:47.440
So our familiarity with
kimchis and fermented foods

00:27:47.440 --> 00:27:50.400
overall is beyond where
it was five years ago.

00:27:50.400 --> 00:27:53.870
So feel free to add whatever
you want to this type of thing

00:27:53.870 --> 00:27:56.500
to make it more fit your palate.

00:27:56.500 --> 00:27:58.180
So that oil is just shimmering.

00:27:58.180 --> 00:28:02.585
Oil obviously is thicker
at a colder temperature

00:28:02.585 --> 00:28:04.400
so it thins out as
it's warming up.

00:28:04.400 --> 00:28:07.820
And you just want to see as
it races down the pan just

00:28:07.820 --> 00:28:09.560
how it's moving.

00:28:09.560 --> 00:28:12.690
But again-- and then we don't
want it to be smoking, though.

00:28:12.690 --> 00:28:14.699
Olive oil has got a
pretty low smoke point.

00:28:14.699 --> 00:28:16.490
You could do this in
a grapeseed oil, which

00:28:16.490 --> 00:28:18.490
is a neutral oil with a
much higher smoke point.

00:28:18.490 --> 00:28:20.300
And that would be good, too.

00:28:20.300 --> 00:28:24.540
And we're not trying to make
popcorn or popped farro, which

00:28:24.540 --> 00:28:25.170
you can make.

00:28:25.170 --> 00:28:26.970
It's actually really good.

00:28:26.970 --> 00:28:32.072
And we're just going to get a
little bit of texture on this.

00:28:32.072 --> 00:28:34.110
So that's all in there.

00:28:34.110 --> 00:28:37.102
I'm going to check on my eggs.

00:28:37.102 --> 00:28:37.810
How are you guys?

00:28:40.690 --> 00:28:43.570
I often cook and
talk to myself a lot.

00:28:43.570 --> 00:28:46.150
That's OK.

00:28:46.150 --> 00:28:50.710
So that's just going to
sizzle out and do its thing.

00:28:53.440 --> 00:28:57.300
And I'm going to
season a little bit.

00:28:57.300 --> 00:28:59.880
Now seasoning is, again, it's
different in every household.

00:28:59.880 --> 00:29:02.120
Just realize what
you want to attain.

00:29:02.120 --> 00:29:06.030
I just want to make sure
the food's fully-- has

00:29:06.030 --> 00:29:08.390
a lot of flavor going on in it.

00:29:08.390 --> 00:29:10.450
So I'm going to
re-emulsify my vinaigrette.

00:29:10.450 --> 00:29:12.400
In the fridge, if it
separates, that's fine.

00:29:12.400 --> 00:29:15.230
Olive oil, when it's cold,
obviously, is pretty solid.

00:29:15.230 --> 00:29:17.160
So you want to take
it out, temp it.

00:29:17.160 --> 00:29:19.180
You can temp it in the
microwave if you need to.

00:29:19.180 --> 00:29:21.984
Nobody uses those
things anymore.

00:29:21.984 --> 00:29:24.400
And then we're going to toss
everything together and begin

00:29:24.400 --> 00:29:26.910
to plate.

00:29:26.910 --> 00:29:28.570
Would my kids eat this?

00:29:28.570 --> 00:29:31.611
Yes, if they were hungry.

00:29:31.611 --> 00:29:33.610
They still am-- I mean,
my kids are not perfect.

00:29:33.610 --> 00:29:35.310
They still jones for
the Chick-fil-As,

00:29:35.310 --> 00:29:37.430
as we've talked about.

00:29:37.430 --> 00:29:39.110
But they would eat this.

00:29:39.110 --> 00:29:44.670
And you could add prosciutto
to it or salumi or whatever

00:29:44.670 --> 00:29:45.500
it may be.

00:29:45.500 --> 00:29:47.820
It's just, to me, this
is the 10-minute meal

00:29:47.820 --> 00:29:50.390
because the farro maybe is
already cooked from last night.

00:29:50.390 --> 00:29:52.940
Basically, the
vinaigrette's already made.

00:29:52.940 --> 00:29:54.960
Basically, you're
giving yourself

00:29:54.960 --> 00:29:57.690
building blocks, which
is exactly what I'm

00:29:57.690 --> 00:30:00.860
trying to give to the kids in
this Seed Life Skills thing.

00:30:00.860 --> 00:30:05.920
So why does this apply to you?

00:30:05.920 --> 00:30:08.360
Because the better you eat,
the more productive you are.

00:30:08.360 --> 00:30:10.170
The better you eat,
the healthier you feel.

00:30:10.170 --> 00:30:12.100
And the better you
eat, the more closely

00:30:12.100 --> 00:30:14.230
you have a relationship
with your kids.

00:30:14.230 --> 00:30:16.160
And the more you cook
food with your kids,

00:30:16.160 --> 00:30:18.722
the more enabled
they are to get--

00:30:18.722 --> 00:30:20.430
to have those life
skills that are really

00:30:20.430 --> 00:30:24.770
going to pertain when they're
out on their own later in life.

00:30:24.770 --> 00:30:25.760
Let's see.

00:30:25.760 --> 00:30:29.070
Let's go over the
basics of the curriculum

00:30:29.070 --> 00:30:30.740
because it's pretty interesting.

00:30:30.740 --> 00:30:34.300
So it's got nine components.

00:30:34.300 --> 00:30:36.090
One of them is life hacks.

00:30:36.090 --> 00:30:37.370
It's leadership.

00:30:37.370 --> 00:30:39.330
It's talking about
how we talk to people

00:30:39.330 --> 00:30:42.910
and how we-- it's
basically the manners.

00:30:42.910 --> 00:30:44.950
When we look at a
dated curriculum,

00:30:44.950 --> 00:30:47.940
there's that manners protocol.

00:30:47.940 --> 00:30:49.740
And somebody was
like, well, do you

00:30:49.740 --> 00:30:51.820
want us to teach
them how to have

00:30:51.820 --> 00:30:53.240
dinner at a fancy restaurant?

00:30:53.240 --> 00:30:55.550
And I'm like, no, I don't care.

00:30:55.550 --> 00:30:58.440
I want you to teach how
to talk to the bank teller

00:30:58.440 --> 00:31:02.890
or how to walk into a
room and feel confident.

00:31:02.890 --> 00:31:05.390
And those are the types of
things that I think they need.

00:31:05.390 --> 00:31:08.390
This is all about
just empowering kids.

00:31:08.390 --> 00:31:09.320
That's it.

00:31:09.320 --> 00:31:14.940
So the second one is kitchen,
home, and health fundamentals.

00:31:14.940 --> 00:31:18.610
Right now, home ec curriculum
spends about a week

00:31:18.610 --> 00:31:23.940
talking about
different sort of risks

00:31:23.940 --> 00:31:27.040
in cooking food and botulism
and all these things.

00:31:27.040 --> 00:31:29.450
And my mandate on
that is they need

00:31:29.450 --> 00:31:31.420
to learn that in
about 15 minutes

00:31:31.420 --> 00:31:33.880
because there are
risks in cooking food.

00:31:33.880 --> 00:31:35.090
And they're there.

00:31:35.090 --> 00:31:38.130
If you're smart about it,
they're rarely, rarely,

00:31:38.130 --> 00:31:39.420
rarely going to happen.

00:31:39.420 --> 00:31:42.140
Botulism cases are
few and far between.

00:31:42.140 --> 00:31:44.950
If you're going a
home canning bent

00:31:44.950 --> 00:31:46.820
and have no idea
what you're doing,

00:31:46.820 --> 00:31:49.124
you're probably on
a dangerous path.

00:31:49.124 --> 00:31:50.790
So as long as you
know what you're doing

00:31:50.790 --> 00:31:54.380
and are following pretty
simple food safety stuff,

00:31:54.380 --> 00:31:56.440
yours should be good to go.

00:31:56.440 --> 00:31:59.250
And then health fundamentals
is how to balance a diet.

00:31:59.250 --> 00:32:00.690
What really is eating?

00:32:00.690 --> 00:32:03.790
Right now, we've got
93% of American kids

00:32:03.790 --> 00:32:05.410
do not eat enough vegetables.

00:32:05.410 --> 00:32:07.060
That's across the board.

00:32:07.060 --> 00:32:09.750
That is from wealthy households
and poor households--

00:32:09.750 --> 00:32:11.760
and at 93%.

00:32:11.760 --> 00:32:13.700
So it's teaching kids
that vegetables are not

00:32:13.700 --> 00:32:15.116
that part of the
plate that you're

00:32:15.116 --> 00:32:16.380
going to feed to the dog.

00:32:16.380 --> 00:32:19.230
But it's that part of the
plate that you really revel in.

00:32:19.230 --> 00:32:21.730
And the only way you get
the kids to eat vegetables

00:32:21.730 --> 00:32:25.320
these days is you start
very, very early in life.

00:32:25.320 --> 00:32:27.570
If a kid doesn't
like a beet at age 2,

00:32:27.570 --> 00:32:30.762
they don't like sugar
because beets are 90% sugar.

00:32:30.762 --> 00:32:31.970
I mean, that's what they are.

00:32:31.970 --> 00:32:34.390
They're like nature's candy.

00:32:34.390 --> 00:32:37.820
So we just need to think
along the lines of how do we--

00:32:37.820 --> 00:32:40.920
but teaching a
15-year-old to eat a beet?

00:32:40.920 --> 00:32:43.920
Have fun with that.

00:32:43.920 --> 00:32:45.990
Let's look over our eggs.

00:32:45.990 --> 00:32:47.850
Our farro's pretty much done.

00:32:47.850 --> 00:32:50.560
I'm just going to spoon just a
little bit of warm liquid on.

00:32:50.560 --> 00:32:53.410
They're just about there.

00:32:53.410 --> 00:32:56.640
As you can see, the egg
white's taken shape.

00:32:56.640 --> 00:33:00.146
The egg yolk is just
beginning to come to temp.

00:33:00.146 --> 00:33:01.820
That's an [INAUDIBLE].

00:33:01.820 --> 00:33:03.530
So we're getting there.

00:33:03.530 --> 00:33:08.060
It just needs a
little bit more time.

00:33:08.060 --> 00:33:11.750
