00:47:08.790 --> 00:47:12.020
AUDIENCE: But I was wondering
if, for you, it was more of a--

00:47:12.020 --> 00:47:13.820
because from a cost
perspective, you're

00:47:13.820 --> 00:47:15.200
just paying way too much.

00:47:15.200 --> 00:47:18.390
Or if it's from a pride in
your cooking perspective,

00:47:18.390 --> 00:47:21.206
that we haven't chosen
the ingredients ourselves.

00:47:21.206 --> 00:47:22.830
HUGH ACHESON: You're
on the right path.

00:47:22.830 --> 00:47:27.170
Look, anything, any
move you can make

00:47:27.170 --> 00:47:29.130
to cook more from
scratch at home--

00:47:29.130 --> 00:47:34.290
and basically these
companies like Blue Apron are

00:47:34.290 --> 00:47:36.940
very smart companies in
kidding you out with mise en

00:47:36.940 --> 00:47:38.570
place so you can cook at home.

00:47:38.570 --> 00:47:41.560
It's just you're really trapped
into their way of thinking.

00:47:41.560 --> 00:47:43.060
And it becomes very expensive.

00:47:43.060 --> 00:47:46.250
What I want to do is make
sure that you understand that

00:47:46.250 --> 00:47:49.970
cooking should be your
adventure, not somebody else's.

00:47:49.970 --> 00:47:52.420
I think you should pick
up a recipe from any book

00:47:52.420 --> 00:47:54.700
or from a magazine
and just embark on it.

00:47:54.700 --> 00:47:56.330
But you need to
be able to atomize

00:47:56.330 --> 00:47:59.550
the skill sets that you're
learning because cooking to me

00:47:59.550 --> 00:48:00.950
is like a LEGO set.

00:48:00.950 --> 00:48:03.370
Each little piece is a
skill set in the kitchen.

00:48:03.370 --> 00:48:06.330
Well, I just have a
bigger LEGO set than you.

00:48:06.330 --> 00:48:09.490
So I can build big things.

00:48:09.490 --> 00:48:12.000
But we all need those LEGO sets.

00:48:12.000 --> 00:48:14.240
And I want you
all to build them.

00:48:14.240 --> 00:48:15.410
But Blue Apron's good.

00:48:15.410 --> 00:48:17.830
And the only other problem
I have with Blue Apron is

00:48:17.830 --> 00:48:20.360
I'm a really,
really big advocate

00:48:20.360 --> 00:48:24.487
of making sure everybody in this
world has the ability to cook.

00:48:24.487 --> 00:48:26.070
And when we talk
about those services,

00:48:26.070 --> 00:48:27.540
they're really expensive.

00:48:27.540 --> 00:48:32.000
So my job is to make sure
that everybody understands--

00:48:32.000 --> 00:48:35.580
from the mother on food
stamps in Detroit--

00:48:35.580 --> 00:48:37.410
this meal is a value.

00:48:37.410 --> 00:48:40.440
This meal is a
value for everybody.

00:48:40.440 --> 00:48:42.090
And it is so easy.

00:48:42.090 --> 00:48:44.920
So there's a complexity
that some of those services

00:48:44.920 --> 00:48:47.200
want to implore you to
cook something complex.

00:48:47.200 --> 00:48:48.440
And I like that.

00:48:48.440 --> 00:48:52.780
First step is the core
idea of food again,

00:48:52.780 --> 00:48:57.240
is the core idea of I want
you to make a salad dressing.

00:48:57.240 --> 00:48:58.420
It's so easy.

00:48:58.420 --> 00:48:59.700
And so that's the idea.

00:48:59.700 --> 00:49:01.960
I want you to make
the perfect omelette

00:49:01.960 --> 00:49:04.803
If you want the best way,
Ludovic Lefebvre of Petit

00:49:04.803 --> 00:49:05.302
Trois.

00:49:05.302 --> 00:49:06.490
And he's on TV.

00:49:06.490 --> 00:49:08.240
He's on "The Taste."

00:49:08.240 --> 00:49:10.880
He's got this amazing
omelette recipe.

00:49:10.880 --> 00:49:12.080
And it's so easy.

00:49:12.080 --> 00:49:14.200
But now Beatrice makes
that omelette all the time

00:49:14.200 --> 00:49:15.780
in this little
French omelette pan.

00:49:15.780 --> 00:49:19.050
I mean, it's the perfect
tri-fold, no color on it,

00:49:19.050 --> 00:49:21.780
just custarded eggs
with chives on top.

00:49:21.780 --> 00:49:23.960
And it's stunning,
finished with butter

00:49:23.960 --> 00:49:26.180
and stuffed with boursin cheese.

00:49:26.180 --> 00:49:29.520
It's not expensive or precious
food, but it's technically on.

00:49:29.520 --> 00:49:30.550
And that's what I want.

00:49:30.550 --> 00:49:33.530
I want people to get so excited
about that type of attribute

00:49:33.530 --> 00:49:37.540
of food that if I can cook an
egg perfectly, I'm winning.

00:49:37.540 --> 00:49:38.040
You know?

00:49:38.040 --> 00:49:40.770
And that, that to me is a
skill set anybody can learn.

00:49:40.770 --> 00:49:42.880
And it's to me it's so exciting.

00:49:42.880 --> 00:49:47.190
And you talked about
changing your child's mood

00:49:47.190 --> 00:49:50.230
when they actually engaged
in something in the kitchen.

00:49:50.230 --> 00:49:54.280
Well, it was because they're
doing something with you.

00:49:54.280 --> 00:49:56.270
And you were doing it together.

00:49:56.270 --> 00:49:58.566
And that, you know, that
to me is like something

00:49:58.566 --> 00:49:59.690
that you can never replace.

00:49:59.690 --> 00:50:02.260
So somebody says, well,
cooking's inconvenient?

00:50:02.260 --> 00:50:04.030
I'll take that
inconvenience every day

00:50:04.030 --> 00:50:06.750
of my life, that connection
I have with my kids

00:50:06.750 --> 00:50:08.980
and watching them
bloom and watching them

00:50:08.980 --> 00:50:10.840
be there and learn something.

00:50:10.840 --> 00:50:11.930
And I had a good time.

00:50:11.930 --> 00:50:13.250
And they got well fed.

00:50:13.250 --> 00:50:14.720
And they learned something.

00:50:14.720 --> 00:50:16.730
And it's just better.

00:50:16.730 --> 00:50:20.430
It's so-- I don't know--
lofty as a dorky goal,

00:50:20.430 --> 00:50:22.880
but so simple as well.

00:50:22.880 --> 00:50:25.240
AUDIENCE: Thanks for all
the content and everything.

00:50:25.240 --> 00:50:26.680
I think it was awesome.

00:50:26.680 --> 00:50:29.460
My question is related
to what you brought up

00:50:29.460 --> 00:50:32.020
about allowing kids to cut.

00:50:32.020 --> 00:50:34.289
I'm actually quite happy
that over the past few months

00:50:34.289 --> 00:50:36.080
I've been involving
the kids in the kitchen

00:50:36.080 --> 00:50:36.913
and stuff like that.

00:50:36.913 --> 00:50:39.480
The one thing-- I have two
kids, an eight-year-old

00:50:39.480 --> 00:50:40.600
and a five-year-old.

00:50:40.600 --> 00:50:43.100
I just had the courage to give
my eight-year-old a knife.

00:50:43.100 --> 00:50:44.789
And he's now chopping
a little bit.

00:50:44.789 --> 00:50:47.080
But I haven't been able to
do it with my five-year-old.

00:50:47.080 --> 00:50:49.670
How could you and what
would you suggest?

00:50:49.670 --> 00:50:53.260
And how can I encourage him to
use a knife but do it right?

00:50:53.260 --> 00:50:54.900
I haven't taught
them right at all.

00:50:54.900 --> 00:50:56.340
They will chop
their fingers soon.

00:50:56.340 --> 00:50:58.430
But I'll try to
do the claw thing.

00:50:58.430 --> 00:51:00.350
HUGH ACHESON: There
are starter knives

00:51:00.350 --> 00:51:02.600
that you can buy at kitchen
supply stores and Williams

00:51:02.600 --> 00:51:05.210
Sonoma and places,
Sur La Table that

00:51:05.210 --> 00:51:07.970
are kind of smaller,
slightly duller knives,

00:51:07.970 --> 00:51:09.077
usually brightly colored.

00:51:12.882 --> 00:51:14.590
The scariest [INAUDIBLE]
from the kitchen

00:51:14.590 --> 00:51:16.910
is a big, very sharp knife.

00:51:16.910 --> 00:51:19.430
But to me, the scariest
knife is a dull knife

00:51:19.430 --> 00:51:21.370
that's going to cut me badly.

00:51:21.370 --> 00:51:24.740
Or the really scary one
is a serrated knife.

00:51:24.740 --> 00:51:26.830
So cutting things that
are difficult to cut

00:51:26.830 --> 00:51:29.340
with a bread knife that's
sharp, bread knives

00:51:29.340 --> 00:51:30.720
will mangle you up.

00:51:30.720 --> 00:51:31.710
So don't do that.

00:51:31.710 --> 00:51:33.790
But just a small,
manageable knife--

00:51:33.790 --> 00:51:37.440
I think a paring
knife-- and just, look,

00:51:37.440 --> 00:51:39.030
if it's a five-
or a six-year-old,

00:51:39.030 --> 00:51:41.240
you have to be there
right there with them.

00:51:41.240 --> 00:51:44.050
You can't turn around.

00:51:44.050 --> 00:51:46.290
But it's training
about, I don't really

00:51:46.290 --> 00:51:47.830
cut myself cutting anymore.

00:51:47.830 --> 00:51:50.350
But I will cut myself
putting my knife in my bag

00:51:50.350 --> 00:51:52.240
or moving around the
kitchen and swiping

00:51:52.240 --> 00:51:55.110
my hand across the
cutting board and pfft.

00:51:55.110 --> 00:52:01.310
So it's reminding a kid
that this is a tool.

00:52:01.310 --> 00:52:02.920
And it's a dangerous tool.

00:52:02.920 --> 00:52:05.500
But it's a really important
tool to learn how to use.

00:52:05.500 --> 00:52:06.866
So we respect it.

00:52:06.866 --> 00:52:08.490
And you lose the
respect for it, you're

00:52:08.490 --> 00:52:09.698
not allowed anywhere near it.

00:52:09.698 --> 00:52:11.080
You have utter respect for it.

00:52:11.080 --> 00:52:14.710
Even at five, kids
will understand that.

00:52:14.710 --> 00:52:17.270
And I think that's a really
important lesson to learn,

00:52:17.270 --> 00:52:19.800
that you can burn
yourself at a stove

00:52:19.800 --> 00:52:21.280
if you're not paying attention.

00:52:21.280 --> 00:52:23.390
You can knock a pot
of water on your foot

00:52:23.390 --> 00:52:25.060
if you're not paying attention.

00:52:25.060 --> 00:52:26.700
That's why we pay
attention in cooking.

00:52:26.700 --> 00:52:28.050
This is serious
in a lot of ways.

00:52:28.050 --> 00:52:30.133
I want you to have a lot
of fun, but it's serious.

00:52:30.133 --> 00:52:35.350
So Clementine gets admonished a
lot, my nine-year-old-- or now

00:52:35.350 --> 00:52:37.894
11-year-old-- for not paying
attention in the kitchen.

00:52:37.894 --> 00:52:39.310
But, you know,
slowly, but surely,

00:52:39.310 --> 00:52:40.900
she understands that if
she wants to be there,

00:52:40.900 --> 00:52:42.570
she's got to take
it pretty seriously.

00:52:42.570 --> 00:52:45.250
So no texting.

00:52:45.250 --> 00:52:46.870
My kids are at that age.

00:52:46.870 --> 00:52:47.822
AUDIENCE: Hi.

00:52:47.822 --> 00:52:48.780
My name is [INAUDIBLE].

00:52:48.780 --> 00:52:50.240
And I just want
to say thank you.

00:52:50.240 --> 00:52:51.240
HUGH ACHESON: Thank you.

00:52:51.240 --> 00:52:55.535
AUDIENCE: I really think
what you're doing is spot on.

00:52:55.535 --> 00:52:57.320
This is something
I've been looking for.

00:52:57.320 --> 00:52:58.620
I have a five-year-old.

00:52:58.620 --> 00:53:03.260
And the last two years-- I'll
just kind of give a story-- we

00:53:03.260 --> 00:53:05.140
set up meals for the week.

00:53:05.140 --> 00:53:08.120
And we allow her, my
daughter, to pick a meal.

00:53:08.120 --> 00:53:09.570
And she'll pick random things.

00:53:09.570 --> 00:53:12.210
Like last week, she
picked French toast.

00:53:12.210 --> 00:53:13.600
And we had it for dinner.

00:53:13.600 --> 00:53:15.690
And we go and find a recipe.

00:53:15.690 --> 00:53:18.630
We force her to write
everything down.

00:53:18.630 --> 00:53:20.380
And we go to the grocery
store and buy it.

00:53:20.380 --> 00:53:21.110
And we make it.

00:53:21.110 --> 00:53:24.660
So that's how we kind of get
her involved in the whole meal

00:53:24.660 --> 00:53:25.160
at home.

00:53:25.160 --> 00:53:30.215
And I think I was just saying
that story because that

00:53:30.215 --> 00:53:31.840
could be something
part of your program

00:53:31.840 --> 00:53:33.197
if that makes some sense.

00:53:33.197 --> 00:53:34.280
HUGH ACHESON: Yeah, it is.

00:53:34.280 --> 00:53:35.863
AUDIENCE: For families,
I mean, that's

00:53:35.863 --> 00:53:37.929
something you could
coordinate relatively easy.

00:53:37.929 --> 00:53:38.720
HUGH ACHESON: Yeah.

00:53:38.720 --> 00:53:43.531
And I think that the idea
of finding a regularity,

00:53:43.531 --> 00:53:46.030
that she's picking a recipe
that she wants to do every week.

00:53:46.030 --> 00:53:49.100
But also, you guys realize
the best written cookbooks

00:53:49.100 --> 00:53:51.020
and the best written
recipes are some the best

00:53:51.020 --> 00:53:55.420
reading you'll ever read because
it's fully instructional.

00:53:55.420 --> 00:53:57.170
And instructional
writing, as you all

00:53:57.170 --> 00:53:59.461
know because a lot of you do
it with what you're doing,

00:53:59.461 --> 00:54:01.980
is really, really difficult.

00:54:01.980 --> 00:54:05.690
We get comments still from
the first cookbook I wrote on,

00:54:05.690 --> 00:54:07.430
it was good, but you
didn't tell me not

00:54:07.430 --> 00:54:09.230
to put the egg shells in there.

00:54:09.230 --> 00:54:14.930
So, you know, I mean, people are
morons when it comes to food.

00:54:14.930 --> 00:54:18.177
So a recipe has to be fully
enveloping of everyone.

00:54:18.177 --> 00:54:19.010
AUDIENCE: It's true.

00:54:19.010 --> 00:54:20.426
HUGH ACHESON: So
it's key for kids

00:54:20.426 --> 00:54:22.740
to read those and
cadence through them.

00:54:22.740 --> 00:54:24.530
And kids are a lot smarter.

00:54:24.530 --> 00:54:28.410
You know, if Beatrice is reading
a recipe, you guys'll scan it.

00:54:28.410 --> 00:54:29.640
You're reading all the time.

00:54:29.640 --> 00:54:30.140
You're busy.

00:54:30.140 --> 00:54:31.880
You'll scan it over
really quickly.

00:54:31.880 --> 00:54:33.560
And it's not really sinking in.

00:54:33.560 --> 00:54:36.630
Beatrice will sit down with
it and take notes first

00:54:36.630 --> 00:54:39.770
and realize, like, sort
of plot out her timeline.

00:54:39.770 --> 00:54:41.900
She's very methodical.

00:54:41.900 --> 00:54:43.600
You can't skim over this.

00:54:43.600 --> 00:54:45.590
We're teaching
kids how to learn.

00:54:45.590 --> 00:54:48.130
So you have to teach them
how to engage with the recipe

00:54:48.130 --> 00:54:50.820
and fully understand it
before they embark on it.

00:54:50.820 --> 00:54:53.240
It's like all of us just
assume that we know how

00:54:53.240 --> 00:54:56.170
to use the gizmos on our car.

00:54:56.170 --> 00:55:01.560
And we just don't because our
cars are so gizmoded out now.

00:55:01.560 --> 00:55:02.840
So it's that type of thing.

00:55:02.840 --> 00:55:05.090
But kids have an amazing
amount of patience

00:55:05.090 --> 00:55:06.740
when you find them
in the right time.

00:55:06.740 --> 00:55:10.740
So I have no problem with a
kid reading that and helping

00:55:10.740 --> 00:55:13.840
me prep it out and showing
the sequence of it.

00:55:13.840 --> 00:55:17.089
And it's beautiful to watch them
sort of get excited about it.

00:55:17.089 --> 00:55:19.130
AUDIENCE: Yeah, I mean,
it was pretty successful.

00:55:19.130 --> 00:55:24.720
But my real question
was, I cook quite a bit.

00:55:24.720 --> 00:55:27.880
And I notice I
use too much salt.

00:55:27.880 --> 00:55:29.690
And I'm just trying
to understand

00:55:29.690 --> 00:55:32.720
what alternates do I have
because eliminating it

00:55:32.720 --> 00:55:35.250
just-- it's not good.

00:55:35.250 --> 00:55:37.720
But I do want to see
a reduction of salt.

00:55:37.720 --> 00:55:40.920
And I don't know if there's
good alternatives that give you

00:55:40.920 --> 00:55:43.769
that flavor as a substitute?

00:55:43.769 --> 00:55:44.560
That's my question.

00:55:46.695 --> 00:55:48.320
HUGH ACHESON: Adding
salt's a hard one.

00:55:48.320 --> 00:55:50.095
I mean, you want to
season appropriately

00:55:50.095 --> 00:55:51.470
to bring stuff
out, but you don't

00:55:51.470 --> 00:55:54.177
want things to taste salty.

00:55:54.177 --> 00:55:56.260
Your doctor is always going
to say you're probably

00:55:56.260 --> 00:55:59.810
ingesting too much salt.
Usually how you're ingesting

00:55:59.810 --> 00:56:02.620
too much salt is you're putting
together a lot of processed

00:56:02.620 --> 00:56:06.560
ingredients that you have
no understanding of how

00:56:06.560 --> 00:56:07.520
much salt's in there.

00:56:07.520 --> 00:56:09.390
When you're adding
the salt yourself

00:56:09.390 --> 00:56:11.880
in a home-cooked
environment from scratch,

00:56:11.880 --> 00:56:13.320
it's at your control.

00:56:13.320 --> 00:56:16.000
So that's the best way of
cooking and controlling

00:56:16.000 --> 00:56:17.290
salt amounts.

00:56:17.290 --> 00:56:19.320
But you want to make
sure-- food that's

00:56:19.320 --> 00:56:21.090
really under-salted is dull.

00:56:21.090 --> 00:56:26.140
So you can add other things
that will amp up flavors.

00:56:26.140 --> 00:56:29.550
So hot sauces and things like
that, or fermented foods.

00:56:29.550 --> 00:56:31.650
But a lot of those contain
a lot of salt, too.

00:56:31.650 --> 00:56:34.330
A slice of bacon is
pretty much enough salt

00:56:34.330 --> 00:56:36.430
as you need the entire
day because the curing

00:56:36.430 --> 00:56:38.810
process of making bacon.

00:56:38.810 --> 00:56:42.060
But then again, if I can find
a nitrate-free one that's

00:56:42.060 --> 00:56:45.600
a little less salt that's really
good and from a local purveyor,

00:56:45.600 --> 00:56:47.580
and I know the ingredients
that went into it

00:56:47.580 --> 00:56:50.380
and I know the veracity
of it, I'm more likely.

00:56:50.380 --> 00:56:53.940
But also-- I don't know--
the last time I checked,

00:56:53.940 --> 00:56:57.110
I just live once, at
least in my belief system.

00:56:57.110 --> 00:57:00.790
And I want to enjoy the food.

00:57:00.790 --> 00:57:01.940
I want to have fun.

00:57:01.940 --> 00:57:03.700
So everything in moderation.

00:57:03.700 --> 00:57:08.350
Look, have fun in life.

00:57:08.350 --> 00:57:10.660
But having fun is
eating good food

00:57:10.660 --> 00:57:13.460
and enjoying it, and enjoying
it with the loved ones

00:57:13.460 --> 00:57:16.390
you have in that amazing room
that you don't use enough

00:57:16.390 --> 00:57:18.490
called your kitchen.

00:57:18.490 --> 00:57:19.400
So enjoy.

00:57:19.400 --> 00:57:23.050
I wouldn't worry too much about
the salt. I'm not a doctor.

00:57:23.050 --> 00:57:26.200
I don't even play one on TV.

00:57:26.200 --> 00:57:27.890
AUDIENCE: Hi.

00:57:27.890 --> 00:57:28.920
My name is Adelle.

00:57:28.920 --> 00:57:31.360
And my daughter
is 21 months old.

00:57:31.360 --> 00:57:33.180
So I've been
struggling with cooking

00:57:33.180 --> 00:57:36.680
for her for the past year.

00:57:36.680 --> 00:57:39.570
So your class is very inspiring.

00:57:39.570 --> 00:57:41.140
And I just have
a quick question.

00:57:41.140 --> 00:57:43.107
When should I start
giving her salad?

00:57:43.107 --> 00:57:45.315
HUGH ACHESON: When should
you start giving her salad?

00:57:45.315 --> 00:57:48.410
AUDIENCE: Because right
now, she wouldn't eat raw.

00:57:48.410 --> 00:57:50.030
She probably would
taste a little bit

00:57:50.030 --> 00:57:54.690
of carrot, but definitely
not a cucumber or radish.

00:57:54.690 --> 00:57:57.140
So what's the approach?

00:57:57.140 --> 00:57:59.660
HUGH ACHESON: What
does she love?

00:57:59.660 --> 00:58:01.760
AUDIENCE: Rice.

00:58:01.760 --> 00:58:03.250
And cheese.

00:58:03.250 --> 00:58:04.364
Yes, she loves cheese.

00:58:04.364 --> 00:58:06.780
HUGH ACHESON: I mean, I would
just start introducing stuff

00:58:06.780 --> 00:58:09.640
slowly, but surely-- tiny,
little cubes of cucumber

00:58:09.640 --> 00:58:13.410
and lightly cooked carrot, and
then moving towards raw stuff.

00:58:13.410 --> 00:58:16.531
Raw vegetables really are
immensely better for you

00:58:16.531 --> 00:58:17.030
overall.

00:58:17.030 --> 00:58:18.530
They're just better
for your system.

00:58:18.530 --> 00:58:21.430
Our bodies are really
trained to eat them well.

00:58:21.430 --> 00:58:24.484
So I think just
slowly, but surely.

00:58:24.484 --> 00:58:26.150
I think you'd be
surprised at what she'd

00:58:26.150 --> 00:58:29.280
eat if she was in a hungry
frame of mind and a good mood,

00:58:29.280 --> 00:58:32.660
and you gave her some rice
and some cheese and three

00:58:32.660 --> 00:58:35.290
other vegetables and you
didn't even talk about it.

00:58:35.290 --> 00:58:36.940
And don't even talk about it.

00:58:36.940 --> 00:58:39.030
It's just stuff on a plate.

00:58:39.030 --> 00:58:40.500
And let her go at it.

00:58:40.500 --> 00:58:42.670
But I think as soon as we
start to question what's

00:58:42.670 --> 00:58:45.520
on the plate, as soon as we
start to territorialize what's

00:58:45.520 --> 00:58:47.660
on the plate as things
that have to be-- that are

00:58:47.660 --> 00:58:49.540
healthy and good
for you, I think

00:58:49.540 --> 00:58:51.360
we ostracize that
part of the plate

00:58:51.360 --> 00:58:53.292
and ostracize it
mentally in their mind

00:58:53.292 --> 00:58:54.750
that they're not
going to go there.

00:58:54.750 --> 00:58:56.860
Or that there's going to
be a fight going there.

00:58:56.860 --> 00:58:59.360
When I don't talk about it,
you see this little thing

00:58:59.360 --> 00:59:00.160
happening.

00:59:00.160 --> 00:59:01.220
You know?

00:59:01.220 --> 00:59:03.630
And sometimes they're like,
oh, I kind of like that.

00:59:03.630 --> 00:59:06.660
And so kids want to go
against us naturally.

00:59:06.660 --> 00:59:08.749
They like that.

00:59:08.749 --> 00:59:09.790
So don't let her do that.

00:59:09.790 --> 00:59:10.600
She's only 21.

00:59:10.600 --> 00:59:13.580
You can take her.

00:59:13.580 --> 00:59:15.470
Don't be pushed around.

00:59:15.470 --> 00:59:17.880
AUDIENCE: I couldn't
help notice this is--

00:59:17.880 --> 00:59:19.420
you made it look so simple.

00:59:19.420 --> 00:59:21.445
And yet it was so tasty,
amazingly delicious.

00:59:21.445 --> 00:59:22.320
HUGH ACHESON: Simple.

00:59:22.320 --> 00:59:23.200
Food.

00:59:23.200 --> 00:59:26.520
AUDIENCE: I had a
question about dressings.

00:59:26.520 --> 00:59:28.830
You mentioned the ratio
as an important component

00:59:28.830 --> 00:59:30.030
to dressing.

00:59:30.030 --> 00:59:32.580
But what other components
can go into a dressing

00:59:32.580 --> 00:59:35.210
to make it appetizing for
someone to have salad?

00:59:35.210 --> 00:59:37.510
I noticed that you didn't
add any sweet component

00:59:37.510 --> 00:59:38.450
to the recipe.

00:59:38.450 --> 00:59:41.949
That's something we find a lot
more in dressings these days.

00:59:41.949 --> 00:59:42.990
HUGH ACHESON: It's weird.

00:59:42.990 --> 00:59:48.310
I grew up-- I have
a strange palate.

00:59:48.310 --> 00:59:49.410
My dad raised us.

00:59:49.410 --> 00:59:50.985
So we ate canned
yellow wax beans

00:59:50.985 --> 00:59:53.420
and burned rice and fish
sticks most of the time.

00:59:53.420 --> 00:59:54.240
So everybody's like,
oh, you must have come

00:59:54.240 --> 00:59:55.990
from a really fancy household.

00:59:55.990 --> 00:59:59.680
And I'm like, no, my dad's a
tenured economics professor.

00:59:59.680 --> 01:00:01.930
He did not feed us well.

01:00:01.930 --> 01:00:02.980
But we ate.

01:00:02.980 --> 01:00:03.710
And it was fine.

01:00:03.710 --> 01:00:06.310
But one thing I never
liked was sugar in food

01:00:06.310 --> 01:00:08.720
that I thought
shouldn't be sweet.

01:00:08.720 --> 01:00:11.610
It just didn't
really work for me.

01:00:11.610 --> 01:00:13.390
And that stuck with me.

01:00:13.390 --> 01:00:18.120
But now there's a big trend
of sugar in savory food.

01:00:18.120 --> 01:00:23.680
And oftentimes it's pulling from
other cultural-- other places

01:00:23.680 --> 01:00:24.670
in the world.

01:00:24.670 --> 01:00:27.500
So Vietnamese cooking has
a lot of cane sugar in it.

01:00:27.500 --> 01:00:29.890
Thai food's got a lot
of cane sugar in it.

01:00:29.890 --> 01:00:33.400
Southern United States food
has a lot of honey and sorghum

01:00:33.400 --> 01:00:35.410
and sugar added to things.

01:00:35.410 --> 01:00:37.120
But that's never been
good for my palate.

01:00:37.120 --> 01:00:39.900
So I keep the vinaigrette
light in that way

01:00:39.900 --> 01:00:41.560
because I don't
want that interplay.

01:00:41.560 --> 01:00:44.570
But you could add a little bit
of-- a tiny bit of molasses

01:00:44.570 --> 01:00:45.390
with soy.

01:00:45.390 --> 01:00:47.325
Soy and molasses go
really well together.

01:00:47.325 --> 01:00:48.783
You could add a
little bit of honey

01:00:48.783 --> 01:00:51.020
or just a really good
honey or something

01:00:51.020 --> 01:00:52.370
like that to broaden it out.

01:00:52.370 --> 01:00:57.910
But really the base ratio of
three to one of oil to vinegar,

01:00:57.910 --> 01:01:00.460
oil to acids, that's
just a foundation.

01:01:00.460 --> 01:01:02.240
You can build up from there.

01:01:02.240 --> 01:01:06.490
So if I took the brine
from dill pickles

01:01:06.490 --> 01:01:10.120
and used that as some of my
acid and made a dill pickle

01:01:10.120 --> 01:01:13.220
vinaigrette and then pureed some
dill pickle to almost thicken

01:01:13.220 --> 01:01:15.365
it up and add a little
contrasting flavor to it,

01:01:15.365 --> 01:01:17.490
you could do that with
sweet and sour pickles, too.

01:01:17.490 --> 01:01:21.030
So you just need to think that
you can make it with anything.

01:01:21.030 --> 01:01:23.070
If you've got leftover
cooked butternut squash

01:01:23.070 --> 01:01:24.900
and have a Vitamix
blender, I can

01:01:24.900 --> 01:01:26.730
make you a butternut
squash vinaigrette

01:01:26.730 --> 01:01:28.560
in about three seconds.

01:01:28.560 --> 01:01:32.030
So you have all this
stuff in your kitchen

01:01:32.030 --> 01:01:34.560
that you never use, like
a slow cooker, a pressure

01:01:34.560 --> 01:01:36.530
cooker, a Vitamix
blender-- all this stuff

01:01:36.530 --> 01:01:38.420
that you've accumulated
over a while.

01:01:38.420 --> 01:01:40.790
Like, if you got married,
and filled out the registry,

01:01:40.790 --> 01:01:42.650
and have all those
crazy, like, when

01:01:42.650 --> 01:01:45.830
was the last time you
used that waffle maker?

01:01:45.830 --> 01:01:49.020
So you just need to realize
that those tools are there

01:01:49.020 --> 01:01:51.560
to make life easier,
but from scratch.

01:01:51.560 --> 01:01:53.262
So just use that base.

01:01:53.262 --> 01:01:54.970
And then you add
whatever you want to it.

01:01:54.970 --> 01:01:57.464
It's whatever flavors
you want can go into it.

01:01:57.464 --> 01:01:58.880
FEMALE SPEAKER:
Thank you so much.

01:01:58.880 --> 01:01:59.379
[APPLAUSE]

01:01:59.379 --> 01:02:01.200
Feel free to come up
and ask us questions.

01:02:01.200 --> 01:02:04.840
And thanks for trying our pilot.

